 with That Which We Have No Ability to Bear":Cultivating Endurance through Digital Connection in Ramadan -- t12. Cyber Dharma: Celebrating E-Vesak in Singapore -- t13. Ritual Adaptations on Telok Ayer: Liturgical Negotiations in a Chinese Temple and a Methodist Church -- t14. Parsis and Ritual Innovation: Zoroastrian Funerary Practices in Mumbai during the Pandemic -- tSection III-Viral Sensorium: Embodiment at a Time of Social Distancing -- t15. "We Knew It!": Caribbean Hindu Responses to Restrictions of Touch during COVID-19 -- t16. A Bread and Wine Issue: "Losing" the Eucharist during the Pandemic -- t17. Touchless Technology, Untouchability,and the COVID-19 Pandemic -- t18. The Sonic and the Somatic: Matua Healing Practices during COVID-19 -- t19. De-sensorializing and Disembodying Chinese Religions in Singapore amid the COVID-19 Pandemic -- t20. Gods Have Eyes: Praying Online in Singapore -- tSection IV-Spatial Sacred Reconfigurations: The "Place" of Religion in the Covidian Age -- t21. The Disruption of Charisma in Southeast Asian Megachurches -- t22. #Minimosque: Cov-Eid as Image, Event, and Archive -- t23. "All of Singapore Is Now a Zawiya": Shadhili Sufism and Sensorial Challenges to Worshiping from Home -- t24. To Go or Not to Go?: Mazu's Annual Procession in Taiwan 2020 -- t25. COVID-19 and Dao Mau's Ritual Practitioners: Shaping the Notion of Social Responsibility -- tSection V-Old Tensions, New Solidarities: Collisions of Faith and Politics -- t26. Sonic Fields of Protection in Sri Lanka's COVID-19 Pandemic -- t27. Seeking Solidarity: Rethinking the Muslim Community in the Pandemic Era -- t28. Serving the Other during the Pandemic: Hindu Nationalist Groups and Covid Relief in India -- t29. Moral Challenges at the Intersection of Religion, Politics,and COVID-19 in Pakistan -- t30. Miracle Cure for COVID-19 in Sri Lanka: Kali and the Politics behind Dhammika Paniya -- t31. COVID-19 and the Rohingyas: Islamic Solidarity and Bottom-Up Initiatives in Aceh -- tSection VI-Religiopolitical Economies of COVID-19: Between Aid and Loss -- t32. Delivering from Suffering in the Final Era: Yiguandao's Response from Aid to Salvation -- t33. The Performance of Hoa Hao Buddhists' Charity Kitchens in Responding to the Coronavirus Pandemic in Vietnam -- t34.The Cap Go Meh That Never Happened -- t35. The Pandemic and Its Effect on the Performance of Hajj Pilgrimage in Malaysia -- t36. Buddhist Temples as Shelters for Vietnamese Migrants in Japan -- t37.Who Owns the Temple Gold? -- t38.COVID-19 and Shifting Practices of Islamic Charity -- tEpilogue -- tReferences -- tContributors -- tIndex0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aBy the summer of 2020, when the coronavirus had fully entered our everyday vocabulary and our lives, religious communities and places of worship around the world were already undergoing profound changes. In Asian and Asian diaspora communities, diverse cultural tropes, beliefs, and artifacts were mobilized to make sense of Covid, including a repertoire of gods and demons like Coronasur, the virus depicted with the horns and fangs of a traditional Hindu demon. Various kinds of knowledge were invoked: theologies, indigenous medicines, and biomedical narratives, as well as ethical values and nationalist sentiments. CoronAsur: Asian Religions in the Covidian Age follows the documentation and analysis of the abrupt societal shifts triggered by the pandemic to understand current and future pandemic times, while revealing further avenues for research on religion that have opened up in the Covidian age. Developed in tandem with the research blog CoronAsur: Religion and COVID-19, this volume is a "phygital" publication, a work grounded in empirical roots as well as digitally born communication. It comprises thirty-eight essays that examine Asian religious communities-Muslim, Buddhist, Hindu, Daoist, and Christian as well as popular/folk and new religious movements, or NRMs-in terms of the changes brought on by and the ritual responses to the Covid pandemic. (Online content, including video and additional images, is available at https://hdl.handle.net/10125/102323.) Studying religious narratives, practices, and changes in the Covidian age adds to our understanding of not only the specific groups in which they are situated, but also the coronavirus itself, its disputed etiologies and culturally contextualized exegeses. CoronAsur offers a comprehensive and timely discussion of Covidian transformations in religious communities' engagements with media, spaces, and moral and political economies, documenting how religious practices and discourses have co-produced the meanings of the pandemic.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCOVID-19 Pandemic, 2020-xReligious aspects. 0aCOVID-19 Pandemic, 2020-zAsiaxReligious aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aasia epidemic.  aasia pandemic.  acoronavirus.  acovid-19 asia.  apublic health coronavirus.  areligion coronavirus.  areligion covid-19.  areligion medicine.  areligion public health.1 aAarshe, Fatema, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArif, Yasmeen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArumugam, Indira, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBagaria, Swayam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBanerjee, Raka, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBhattacharjee, Malini, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBhuiyan, Md. Khaled Bin Oli, 